# perf_nzmap_ab — paired port-BEFORE vs port-AFTER wall A/B for the nz-map SIMD kernel
date: 2026-07-23T21:00:01Z
host: dev-32gb (16 cores)
before: master 16d9c296a scan-order scalar (binary /tmp/perf_encode_before)
after:  perf/nzmap-simd 366bf42c3 raster SIMD dispatch (binary /tmp/perf_encode_after)
harness: both PORT binaries interleaved per round in randomized order (same pairing
  design as tools/perf_gate.sh, but the pair is before/after instead of port/C), so
  machine drift cancels within each pair. 40 rounds/cell, gradient qp40, release,
  no target-cpu=native, warmup 1. Per-cell identity pre-check: before .obu ==
  after .obu asserted before any timing (0 failures).
load context: the box ran other agents' steady jobs throughout (1-min loadavg
  ~13.4-14.9, recorded per round in the raw TSV). Steady symmetric contention
  inflates ABSOLUTE ms (~1.8x vs the clean-box perf_nzmap-before-master sweep) but
  cancels in the per-round paired RATIO — the honest metric here. The separate
  perf_nzmap-after sweep is load-contaminated (see its .meta) and is NOT evidence.
verdict: KEEP — every cell's paired median ratio < 1:

